1
00:00:04,295 --> 00:00:05,171
Karen!

2
00:00:06,131 --> 00:00:09,968
Uh, K-Kar... Karen... What's the deal?
Did you not see me?

3
00:00:10,051 --> 00:00:11,970
Of course I did,
but I ran because your face says

4
00:00:12,053 --> 00:00:13,179
you want money for something.

5
00:00:13,263 --> 00:00:14,389
Oh, well, yeah, I do.

6
00:00:14,472 --> 00:00:16,891
What is it today?
Therapy dogs for postpartum mothers?

7
00:00:16,975 --> 00:00:19,352
Improv classes for survivors of PTSD?

8
00:00:19,436 --> 00:00:22,856
Uh, no, good idea, both of those,
but I was thinking that, um...

9
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:29,946
-I want to end systemic racism.
-Oh, for God's sake.

10
00:00:30,030 --> 00:00:31,990
No, just at the hospital.
Start small, right?

11
00:00:32,073 --> 00:00:35,368
Wow, kind of controversial stance,
walking away, siding with racism.

12
00:00:35,452 --> 00:00:36,661
Kind of a Karen move, Karen.

13
00:00:36,745 --> 00:00:40,206
My exasperation with you has no relation
to my thoughts on racism.

14
00:00:41,332 --> 00:00:43,626
-Why today, Max?
-Knew you were going to ask that.

15
00:00:43,710 --> 00:00:46,087
There is no answer.
We should be asking the right question,

16
00:00:46,171 --> 00:00:48,173
which is, why not yesterday?
Why not a year ago?

17
00:00:48,256 --> 00:00:50,383
Why not two years ago
when I first took over?

18
00:00:50,467 --> 00:00:52,844
Systemic racism
should have been the first thing

19
00:00:52,927 --> 00:00:55,930
I addressed when I got to New Amsterdam
and I'm appalled that it wasn't.

20
00:00:56,014 --> 00:00:58,475
-So today it is.
-And you need money for...

21
00:00:58,558 --> 00:01:00,935
A new position,
someone to help us identify

22
00:01:01,019 --> 00:01:02,979
and eliminate systemic marginalization

23
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:05,440
while correcting inequities
throughout the whole hospital.

24
00:01:05,523 --> 00:01:07,275
You want a chief equity officer?

25
00:01:07,358 --> 00:01:09,444
Yeah, that's perfect. We'll call it that.

26
00:01:09,527 --> 00:01:12,197
Oh and I am not going anywhere
until you give me one.

27
00:01:12,530 --> 00:01:15,700
Well, in that case, go away,
because we already have one.

28
00:01:17,494 --> 00:01:18,369
We do?

29
00:01:24,793 --> 00:01:26,920
-Hey.
-Oh, hi there. Uh...

30
00:01:27,003 --> 00:01:27,921
Are you...

31
00:01:28,922 --> 00:01:31,257
Let's see here. Isabel?

32
00:01:31,341 --> 00:01:33,802
-Yes.
-Great, I'm Max Goodwin, medical director.

33
00:01:33,885 --> 00:01:34,969
How can I help?

34
00:01:36,179 --> 00:01:37,472
I see what you did there.

35
00:01:37,555 --> 00:01:43,478
Um, yeah, I'm here to discuss
some pretty disturbing, uh, statistics.

36
00:01:43,561 --> 00:01:44,604
-Hit me.
-Okay.

37
00:01:44,687 --> 00:01:47,357
Well, according to the latest report
by Health and Human Services,

38
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:51,027
Latinx women are 40% more likely
to have cervical cancer

39
00:01:51,111 --> 00:01:54,072
and 20% more likely to die from it
than white women.

40
00:01:54,155 --> 00:01:57,075
Indigenous Americans
have twice the HIV infection rate

41
00:01:57,158 --> 00:01:58,827
as that of non-Hispanic whites.

42
00:01:58,910 --> 00:02:01,579
Black women are two to six times

43
00:02:01,663 --> 00:02:05,291
more likely to die from complications
of pregnancy than white women.

44
00:02:05,375 --> 00:02:07,794
Actually, it's 12 times more likely
in New York City.

45
00:02:08,670 --> 00:02:11,589
Your statistics are a bit... generic.

46
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:12,549
Oh.

47
00:02:12,924 --> 00:02:15,135
-How long have you worked here?
-Three years.

48
00:02:15,218 --> 00:02:17,220
Three... three years?

49
00:02:18,346 --> 00:02:20,056
Well, we have a lot of work to do.

50
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:23,810
That's exactly what
I say to you in my messages.

51
00:02:24,727 --> 00:02:26,855
Once a week,
I leave word with your office,

52
00:02:26,938 --> 00:02:28,773
hoping to get some time with you.

53
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:32,986
Sorry, sometimes,
with this hospital, I'm just running

54
00:02:33,069 --> 00:02:35,071
and, uh... Not important. Listen.

55
00:02:35,905 --> 00:02:37,949
-I'm here now, okay?
-Okay.

56
00:02:38,032 --> 00:02:39,492
And we are going to fix this.

57
00:02:40,243 --> 00:02:43,121
So I want innovative proposals
on my desk by tomorrow.

58
00:02:43,204 --> 00:02:47,250
And think big. You know, get creative.
No solution is off the table.

59
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:50,837
Should we start with acknowledging
New Amsterdam's biggest illustration

60
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:52,255
of embedded systemic racism?

61
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:54,883
Yes, yes, of course. What is it?

62
00:02:55,174 --> 00:02:56,426
You.

63
00:03:02,432 --> 00:03:04,767
{\an8}-Good read?
-Don't get me started.

64
00:03:04,851 --> 00:03:06,269
{\an8}Actually, do get me started.

65
00:03:06,352 --> 00:03:08,521
{\an8}I've been made executor
of my brother's will

66
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:11,274
{\an8}-and I haven't the foggiest.
-I thought you two weren't close.

67
00:03:11,357 --> 00:03:15,486
{\an8}Well, we weren't, but now I'm in charge
of his house, his car, his saxophones.

68
00:03:15,570 --> 00:03:18,615
{\an8}The only thing I'm confident about is
making arrangements for his daughter Mina

69
00:03:18,698 --> 00:03:21,826
{\an8}to live with her aunt in Dubai...
[chuckles] in an actual palace.

70
00:03:21,910 --> 00:03:23,119
{\an8}You have a niece.

71
00:03:23,202 --> 00:03:25,580
{\an8}And a rich second aunt
who doesn't want my brother's boat

72
00:03:25,663 --> 00:03:27,290
{\an8}because she already has several.

73
00:03:27,373 --> 00:03:30,418
{\an8}Well, you keep it.
We could spend our vacation at sea.

74
00:03:30,501 --> 00:03:33,379
{\an8}Sky, the waves, you and me.

75
00:03:34,130 --> 00:03:35,131
{\an8}It's a rowboat.

76
00:03:35,632 --> 00:03:37,133
{\an8}Then Bora Bora it is.

77
00:03:39,093 --> 00:03:41,554
{\an8}So did you like the rest
of <i>Catcher in the Rye?</i>

78
00:03:42,805 --> 00:03:44,307
{\an8}What about that red hunting hat, man?

79
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:46,226
{\an8}I thought that would be
right up your alley.

80
00:03:46,309 --> 00:03:49,187
{\an8}-Mm, it was fine.
-It was fine.

81
00:03:49,854 --> 00:03:52,523
{\an8}You, uh... you talked my ear off
about the Ducks last session.

82
00:03:52,607 --> 00:03:54,400
{\an8}The red hunting hat is way more important.

83
00:03:54,901 --> 00:03:55,944
{\an8}[grunts softly]

84
00:03:56,027 --> 00:03:58,655
{\an8}Oh, I'm sorry. What's up with your hand?

85
00:03:59,405 --> 00:04:01,115
{\an8}I... I fell on it wrong.

86
00:04:01,199 --> 00:04:03,159
{\an8}Oh, okay. Well, just in case,
let me take a look.

87
00:04:03,243 --> 00:04:04,244
It's fine.

88
00:04:05,286 --> 00:04:08,748
{\an8}That's a little too much <i>fine</i>
for one session, Ollie. Let me see.

89
00:04:13,378 --> 00:04:15,630
{\an8}Radiology's slammed,
but they'll fit him in right away.

90
00:04:15,713 --> 00:04:18,883
{\an8}Okay, thank you. See that, buddy?
VIP treatment for you, right?

91
00:04:19,384 --> 00:04:20,385
{\an8}What happened?

92
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:31,729
{\an8}Uh, he said he fell.

93
00:04:32,647 --> 00:04:35,024
{\an8}No, Mama, last night, I separated them all

94
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:37,777
{\an8}and put them
in your monthly pill organizer, remember?

95
00:04:38,486 --> 00:04:41,322
{\an8}Yes, of course you can still call me
whenever you want, but...

96
00:04:41,406 --> 00:04:45,451
No, but take the yellow pill now,
the yellow pill while I'm on the phone.

97
00:04:46,035 --> 00:04:46,911
[door bangs open]

98
00:04:46,995 --> 00:04:48,121
Incoming!

99
00:04:48,204 --> 00:04:50,331
A tour bus jumped the curb
in Times Square.

100
00:04:50,415 --> 00:04:52,000
Superman may have a fractured wrist,

101
00:04:52,083 --> 00:04:54,043
but he won't stay put long enough
for me to check.

102
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:56,462
-Okay, what's his real name?
-ID says Murph Coleman,

103
00:04:56,546 --> 00:04:58,506
but he only responds to Superman.

104
00:04:58,589 --> 00:05:01,175
Kebir Abad,
38-year-old male falafel vendor.

105
00:05:01,259 --> 00:05:03,511
Second-degree hot oil burns
covering both arms.

106
00:05:03,594 --> 00:05:05,388
-[groaning]
-Superman, get back in your chair.

107
00:05:05,471 --> 00:05:06,848
Not till this man's in bay 24!

108
00:05:06,931 --> 00:05:08,182
-Hammond!
-On it.

109
00:05:08,933 --> 00:05:11,060
Skelly, Williams, team three, bed five.

110
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:13,187
Hey, you got to hold this, okay?
It's important.

111
00:05:13,271 --> 00:05:15,189
Stable vitals? Team one, bed nine.

112
00:05:15,273 --> 00:05:17,150
You okay? You got to keep your eyes open.

113
00:05:17,233 --> 00:05:19,068
-Someone get me Cassian.
-All right.

114
00:05:19,152 --> 00:05:20,737
-Let's do it.
-You going to be okay?

115
00:05:20,820 --> 00:05:22,071
-Got to go.
-I can't...

116
00:05:22,155 --> 00:05:24,157
Come on. Let's not back up triage.

117
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,199
Hammond.

118
00:05:26,117 --> 00:05:27,744
-[sighs] Hammond!
-[grunting]

119
00:05:27,827 --> 00:05:31,289
-Sorry. He really is faster than...
-Do not! Just get him back in his chair.

120
00:05:31,372 --> 00:05:34,792
Wilmer Belasco, male, 42 years old.
Blunt force trauma to the chest.

121
00:05:34,876 --> 00:05:38,796
Heart rate 113, BP 161 over 98.
Possible cracked sternum.

122
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:40,631
-My boy...
-Don't try to talk. Mr. Belasco.

123
00:05:40,715 --> 00:05:41,591
Hector Belasco,

124
00:05:41,674 --> 00:05:44,343
-13-year-old boy BP 126 over 87.
-That's my son!

125
00:05:44,427 --> 00:05:45,970
Lauren, I got him. I got him.

126
00:05:46,054 --> 00:05:48,097
-[muffled speech]
-Doc, no!

127
00:05:48,181 --> 00:05:51,726
-[Floyd] He's going to be taken care of.
-Hi, Hector, I'm Dr. Shin. It's okay.

128
00:05:51,809 --> 00:05:54,937
-We're going to take good care of you.
-Bilateral compound femur fracture,

129
00:05:55,021 --> 00:05:58,107
-possible hypovolemic shock from injuries.
-Okay, let's take a look.

130
00:05:59,650 --> 00:06:02,487
-[screams]
-[both yelling, screaming]

131
00:06:02,570 --> 00:06:03,613
Trauma one.

132
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:07,325
-Dad!
-[yelling in Spanish]

133
00:06:10,453 --> 00:06:11,621
Sir.

134
00:06:14,791 --> 00:06:16,292
-In the chair, Superman.
-But I just...

135
00:06:16,375 --> 00:06:17,502
Stay put.

136
00:06:18,628 --> 00:06:20,630
[phone vibrating]

137
00:06:22,632 --> 00:06:24,675
<i>How could you do this to me?</i>

138
00:06:24,759 --> 00:06:26,094
<i>I'm not going to Dubai.</i>

139
00:06:26,177 --> 00:06:29,222
Mina, um, so just give me a second to...

140
00:06:29,305 --> 00:06:32,308
<i>I have friends, a boyfriend,
a whole life here.</i>

141
00:06:32,391 --> 00:06:35,686
<i>If you had bothered to call me
after my father died,</i>

142
00:06:35,770 --> 00:06:38,439
<i>you'd know that.</i>

143
00:06:38,523 --> 00:06:40,441
<i>Do you know how far Dubai is from Tehran?</i>

144
00:06:40,525 --> 00:06:41,984
Mina, I know that it's hard,

145
00:06:42,068 --> 00:06:44,362
but I'm sure your dad would've wanted you
to be with family.

146
00:06:44,445 --> 00:06:46,280
You know nothing about my father.

147
00:06:50,159 --> 00:06:52,912
-Can I talk to you a second?
-Can it wait? I just got...

148
00:06:52,995 --> 00:06:56,749
No, uh, I just made a commitment to ending
the inherent and systemic racism

149
00:06:56,833 --> 00:06:59,043
here at this hospital
and I know what I need to do.

150
00:06:59,127 --> 00:07:01,587
-[clears throat] Max...
-I'm stepping down as medical director.

151
00:07:03,339 --> 00:07:04,590
Who is taking over?

152
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:06,634
You are.

153
00:07:07,468 --> 00:07:08,886
[breathes heavily]

154
00:07:12,265 --> 00:07:14,475
You want me to be medical director?

155
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:16,561
-Yeah.
-And you, you'll just...

156
00:07:16,644 --> 00:07:18,771
Quietly recede into a supporting role.

157
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:22,024
-You've never done anything quietly.
-Yeah, I know. That's exactly the problem.

158
00:07:22,108 --> 00:07:24,110
I tried to force an initiative
on Black barber shops

159
00:07:24,193 --> 00:07:25,987
to get them to turn into
community health ops.

160
00:07:26,070 --> 00:07:29,866
I have called the WHO every single day
for three months, three months,

161
00:07:29,949 --> 00:07:32,535
trying to get racism
coded as a health risk

162
00:07:32,618 --> 00:07:37,498
and now I realize that none of it was ever
actually going to change anything,

163
00:07:37,582 --> 00:07:39,542
because I am part of the problem.

164
00:07:39,625 --> 00:07:41,335
-Says who?
-My chief equity officer.

165
00:07:41,419 --> 00:07:43,171
[chuckles] We have a chief equity officer?

166
00:07:43,254 --> 00:07:44,547
Yeah, Isabel. She's very sweet.

167
00:07:44,630 --> 00:07:47,425
But as women of color,
you are both vastly under... Hi.

168
00:07:47,508 --> 00:07:49,719
...underrepresented in management,

169
00:07:49,802 --> 00:07:52,388
which makes you much less likely
to get a promotion

170
00:07:52,472 --> 00:07:55,892
and therefore not in a position
to then hire other women of color,

171
00:07:55,975 --> 00:07:59,812
so it's a vicious cycle really,
but the thing is it can be changed

172
00:07:59,896 --> 00:08:02,648
if a woman of color is at the top,
which is exactly why

173
00:08:02,732 --> 00:08:04,484
you need to say yes to this job.

174
00:08:04,567 --> 00:08:07,320
-No.
-You could do a lot of good.

175
00:08:07,403 --> 00:08:10,156
Here I thought I was doing good,
being an oncologist.

176
00:08:10,239 --> 00:08:11,449
More good.

177
00:08:11,866 --> 00:08:13,743
Do you not see the irony in asking someone

178
00:08:13,826 --> 00:08:16,412
who's suffering from systemic racism
to also fix it?

179
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:20,208
Well, does that mean you'll consider it?

180
00:08:21,375 --> 00:08:24,378
Okay, no, Helen, I...
Oh, I don't know where to start!

181
00:08:24,462 --> 00:08:25,755
Just look to your right.

182
00:08:36,474 --> 00:08:37,934
Hey, you are going to be just fine.

183
00:08:38,017 --> 00:08:40,019
I got him down in a wheelchair,
but he got up again.

184
00:08:40,102 --> 00:08:41,938
-Here we go!
-Superman, stay in the chair!

185
00:08:42,021 --> 00:08:45,900
Have Walsh clear Superman's wrist
and escort him out of here, okay?

186
00:08:46,567 --> 00:08:47,985
-Where am I going?
-Hey!

187
00:08:48,069 --> 00:08:50,196
Hey, this has to get to the trauma room.

188
00:08:50,279 --> 00:08:52,406
This is Mr. Abad.
Before his car flipped over,

189
00:08:52,490 --> 00:08:55,535
-he saw the whole accident.
-Hammond, do not let him into trauma one.

190
00:08:55,618 --> 00:08:56,911
Doing the best I can.

191
00:08:56,994 --> 00:08:57,954
Right here.

192
00:08:58,996 --> 00:09:00,331
[grunts] Hey!

193
00:09:00,414 --> 00:09:03,000
Right before his car tipped over,
he saw the whole accident.

194
00:09:03,084 --> 00:09:04,669
Tell Dr. Bloom what you just told me.

195
00:09:05,169 --> 00:09:07,088
It was the craziest thing I've ever seen.

196
00:09:07,171 --> 00:09:08,965
The minute the bus jumped the curb,

197
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:10,508
everybody started running,

198
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:12,468
Except for Superman!

199
00:09:13,386 --> 00:09:14,512
[chuckles]

200
00:09:15,179 --> 00:09:17,932
-He just stood there.
-Why?

201
00:09:18,015 --> 00:09:20,601
No idea, but he took the hit like a champ.

202
00:09:21,185 --> 00:09:22,562
I hope someone got video.

203
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:26,357
-Superman got hit by the bus?
-Hard.

204
00:09:26,899 --> 00:09:28,651
I don't know he's still standing.

205
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:32,572
-Well, he is the Man of S...
-Don't say it.

206
00:09:32,655 --> 00:09:33,990
Page neurology now.

207
00:09:37,243 --> 00:09:38,578
I've got 52 bones.

208
00:09:43,291 --> 00:09:44,917
Did you hear that Ollie hurt his hand?

209
00:09:45,918 --> 00:09:46,752
Yes.

210
00:09:47,837 --> 00:09:49,005
It's really bad.

211
00:09:50,339 --> 00:09:52,550
I'm a doctor
and I can't even figure out what happened.

212
00:09:54,302 --> 00:09:56,887
I'm not stupid. I know you think I did it.

213
00:09:57,263 --> 00:09:58,139
Did you?

214
00:09:59,807 --> 00:10:02,560
I had to. I had no choice.

215
00:10:05,855 --> 00:10:07,898
Juliet, you were making such progress.

216
00:10:07,982 --> 00:10:11,319
He insulted my brother, my parents.

217
00:10:11,986 --> 00:10:13,613
I was defending their honor.

218
00:10:13,696 --> 00:10:15,323
You were defending their honor?

219
00:10:15,406 --> 00:10:19,368
When I took the vow of the samurai,
I took the vow to the death.

220
00:10:19,994 --> 00:10:21,787
-Is this a joke to you?
-Sure.

221
00:10:22,121 --> 00:10:23,331
Because I didn't do it.

222
00:10:24,582 --> 00:10:26,000
Okay. [clears throat]

223
00:10:27,126 --> 00:10:30,379
Juliet, do you remember the rules
of the game that we've been playing?

224
00:10:30,463 --> 00:10:31,631
Expert level.

225
00:10:32,131 --> 00:10:34,759
I only win
if the loser doesn't think they lost.

226
00:10:34,842 --> 00:10:37,803
If I upset them or hurt them, I lose.

227
00:10:37,887 --> 00:10:38,929
Correct.

228
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:42,850
So when you smashed Ollie's hand,
you lost.

229
00:10:42,933 --> 00:10:46,395
Except I didn't smash Ollie's hand.

230
00:10:47,104 --> 00:10:48,606
I was joking.

231
00:10:49,106 --> 00:10:51,067
I don't think you're telling the truth.

232
00:10:52,485 --> 00:10:53,819
Right now or before?

233
00:10:53,903 --> 00:10:55,905
Now. I think
you're lying to protect yourself.

234
00:10:55,988 --> 00:10:58,366
-Final answer?
-This is not a game, Juliet.

235
00:10:58,449 --> 00:10:59,867
This is not the game!

236
00:11:06,248 --> 00:11:07,249
Okay.

